<br>
I don't think he does for a second. I think he uses it as a tool and rallying point to further his organization's agendas in the same way that any politician uses affiliations, religious or otherwise, to further their political and personal interests.<br>
<br>
I'm sure he's not a dumb guy, and coming from where he did to a desperately poor part of the world figured out early he could be on the superhighway to political success and making his personal beliefs reality. With his obvious personal beliefs and agenda with the West that the have-nots in that part of the world can identify with, that religious affiliation, and his extremely deep pockets courtesy of his billionaire family he's practically the middle east version of a Kennedy. I'm sure tons of radicals there have the first two, but the last one was what got him where he is, gaining status in the mujahaddin and later with the Taliban due to his ability to finance them from his fat bank account. Osama knew it's all about the Benjamins and played it that way. I don't think Islam, Allah, or Jihad are reasons for anything he does, he's just a pissed off self-righteous guy who uses them as vehicles to get his work done.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 321<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/4/02 2:30 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=284.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Islamic Fundamentalism?</span><hr size=1> I dunno... I think without knowing a lot more about him personally, it would be hard to say either way.  I think it is fair to say, however, that a very large amount of the Middle Eastern culture is based around their religion, and that it plays a large part in the lives of many people who live there, especially in the more theological nations like Saudi Arabia, Iran, etc.  Therefore the issue remains even if bin Laden is truly only concerned with secular power politics and not religion per se... which I personally doubt, but like I said, have no basis for that opinion other than a cursory knowledge of the region he comes from and its history.<br>
<br>
The concept therefore applies not only to him personally, but to the whole Middle East and Islam in general.  That is the focus of the excerpt... is this Islam in the process of going the way of Western Europe?  Or is it simply an affirmation of their general devotion to their religion?  I had never even considered the former as a possibility, but Warren makes a good argument.  I'm not really sure myself. <p>Caledhon TelRana - Champion<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701"><br>
