 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maxamaji>MaxaMaji</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 641<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/4/02 3:43 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=284.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Islamic Fundamentalism?</span><hr size=1> Yeah, I have no basis for it either except my gut instinct and the fact that on a basic level people are the same regardless of where they're from. It's hard for me to believe that anyone would go to the lengths he does for pure religious fundamentalism. Religious fundamentalism is religious fundamentalism no matter what the religion, and when we see types with his level of following here, there are always factors other than just furthering the beliefs of the religion. Everyday lust for power, personal gain, or personal agenda almost always play some part in it. Only difference being that over there religion is sponsored by the state (or other way around), lending it more credibility to the public. <br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 322<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/6/02 6:04 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=284.topic&index=6>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Islamic Fundamentalism?</span><hr size=1> Don't assume that merely because you have become to one degree or another cynical and jaded about people's motivations, that everyone in the world has too.  Shockingly enough, people exist who truly believe in things like religions and ideologies...<br>
<br>
One of the foundations of modern liberalism (used in the &quot;classical&quot; sense) is the ability to &quot;agree to disagree&quot;, and therefore recognize that fundamental differences between yourself and other people exist, but that you can each ignore them and work around them.  It is something that people like bin Laden, Wahabbi Muslims, and handfuls of both political and religious extremists here and there cannot grasp.  Without it, democracy could not exist... whenever one actor wins, the other stages a revolt because they cannot live with the results.  It's why so many Third World nations simply cannot function with a democratic government in place.  Its presence in American society is why even people who believe strongly in their religion or ideology can get along without resorting to the sort of action that bin Laden has taken.  People all around you live with beliefs, be they secular or religious, just as strong as bin Laden or the 9/11 hijackers had... the difference is that they don't run around running planes into tall buildings to get their policies enacted. <p>Caledhon TelRana - Champion<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701"><br>
