</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maxamaji>MaxaMaji</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/globalWhite.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read boards more<br>than I play EQ....</span><br>  Posts: 643<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/7/02 9:10 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=284.topic&index=7>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Islamic Fundamentalism?</span><hr size=1> Likewise, don't assume because you've never seen it that ulterior motives don't exist a lot more often than is evident. Realistic viewpoint maybe, but hardly cynical and jaded. Very seldom are the motivations of people, especially in positions of power over other people such as his, as pure as they come across. They usually can't be in order to keep the operation afloat. No different than the fact that very seldom are the motivations of anyone you meet on the street as pure as they come across, but become close friends with them and you might find what those real motivations are. It's not an earth-shattering concept or a *bad thing*, just a fact of life.<br>
<br>
Religious zealots in the US don't fly planes into buildings because their religion is not supported by the state and they don't have the support that the groups have over there. Were they given the ability to, there's fundamentalist religious groups here that would do the same things as al qaeda. The issue is not everyday people with strong beliefs, they're a dime a dozen, it's people with strong beliefs with the means to make things happen. Very often that means is money. Depending on what they're trying to accomplish determines how powerful that leader needs to be. Overcoming the inertia of a juggernaut like the US government is a far cry from overthrowing the brand new government of a poor third world country. The latter is realistic for an individual or small group while the former is not. That is why they get overthrown and we do not, not &quot;the ability to get along&quot;.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=caledhontelrana>Caledhon TelRana</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 323<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(12/7/02 10:36 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=284.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Islamic Fundamentalism?</span><hr size=1> Obviously its more complex than the one factor I listed, but what it boils down to is legitimacy, and how much each actor &quot;believes in the system&quot;.  The ability to &quot;get along&quot; is a simplified way to talk about a nation and its people's political culture - one of tolerance, or rigidity?  Why is a coup unimaginable in the United States, yet common in Latin America?  Or a better example... Japan... it doesn't have much of a military, and there are states nearby (China, North Korea) which would likely love to see a government in power less friendly to the U.S... but how likely is it that the Japanese will revert to a military autocracy?  Not very.  The sheer power and size of a government can prevent coups - this is why dictatorships survive - but for a democracy to live past its infancy, there must be that sense of civic culture present.<br>
<br>
As to the other more on topic point, yeah... people are going to act in their self interest.  But their self interest is not always based purely upon personal advancement... for religious fundamentalists, it is often the advancement of their organization, or their God (as they see it), and for these they will do almost anything.  Even if it may not be the best thing for the person themself, if they believe strongly enough that it is in the best interest of their God or their religion, strongly enough, then they will do things like the old Christian martyrs did, or the Jews who refused to convert during the Inquisition, or the Muslims who fly planes into buildings now... each is an act of supreme faith, there can be no doubt.  Unfortunately faith can be twisted, people can be manipulated, or the basis of the faith can even be corrupt and call upon people to do evil things... but that is not an argument for this thread. <p>Caledhon TelRana - Champion<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=51701"><br>
